    slug: "framer-headless-wordpress-best-of-both-worlds",
    title: "Framer and Headless WordPress — The Best of Both Worlds",
    excerpt: "Combine Framer's design power with WordPress's content management by setting up a headless CMS architecture.",
    content: "<p>Framer delivers exceptional design capabilities and performance, but some projects require a content management system more powerful than Framer's built-in CMS — one that supports complex content relationships, custom fields, user roles, revision history, and a mature editorial workflow. WordPress, which powers over 43% of all websites on the internet, offers exactly that. By using WordPress as a headless CMS — meaning it handles content creation and management while Framer handles the frontend presentation — you get the best of both worlds: WordPress's unmatched content management ecosystem paired with Framer's pixel-perfect design output and blazing-fast static hosting. This hybrid architecture is becoming increasingly popular for content-heavy websites that refuse to compromise on either content management or design quality.</p><h2>Setting Up WordPress as a Headless CMS</h2><p>Headless WordPress means using WordPress only for its admin panel and content API, not for rendering the frontend. WordPress has included a REST API since version 4.7, exposing posts, pages, categories, tags, custom post types, and custom fields as JSON endpoints that any frontend can consume. To set up your headless WordPress instance, start with a standard WordPress installation on any hosting provider — WP Engine, Kinsta, or even a basic shared host will work since the server only handles API requests, not front-end traffic. Install Advanced Custom Fields (ACF) to create structured content models beyond the default posts and pages — this lets you define custom field groups for template sections, team members, portfolio projects, or any content type your site requires. The ACF to REST API plugin exposes your custom fields through the WordPress API. For authentication, install the JWT Authentication plugin so your Framer site can make authenticated API calls to access draft content during development. Disable the default WordPress theme and frontend completely by redirecting the WordPress URL to your Framer domain, keeping the admin panel accessible at the /wp-admin path.</p><h2>Fetching WordPress Content in Framer</h2><p>Framer's data fetching capabilities let you pull content from external APIs and bind it to your design components. Use the fetch function in Framer's code components to request data from your WordPress REST API endpoints. A basic fetch call to yourdomain.com/wp-json/wp/v2/posts returns your latest blog posts as a JSON array, which you can then map to Framer's CMS-style collection layouts. For individual post pages, use dynamic routing in Framer combined with slug-based API queries to render each post with its full content. Images stored in the WordPress media library are accessible through the API's media endpoints or embedded directly in post content — use the featured_media field to fetch hero images for cards and list views. Create a dedicated code component in Framer that handles the API connection, error states, and loading indicators, then reuse it across your collection and detail pages. Cache API responses where possible to reduce load times and minimize API calls to your WordPress server.</p><h2>When to Use This Architecture and When to Avoid It</h2><p>The headless WordPress plus Framer architecture shines for specific use cases: content-heavy blogs with multiple editors who need a familiar publishing interface, media outlets that require WordPress's editorial workflow features, businesses with existing WordPress content libraries they do not want to migrate, and projects that need WordPress's ecosystem of over 50,000 plugins for backend functionality. This setup is overkill for simple marketing sites, portfolios, or landing pages where Framer's native CMS handles content needs adequately. The main trade-offs are increased complexity — you are now maintaining two systems instead of one — and potential API latency that can affect page load times if not properly cached. You also lose some of Framer's real-time preview capabilities since content changes in WordPress require re-fetching data. For template creators on Flowbites, offering a Framer template pre-configured with headless WordPress integration is a significant value-add that commands premium pricing. Include detailed setup documentation, a starter WordPress theme with the necessary plugins pre-configured, and example code components that demonstrate the API integration pattern for common content types.</p>",
