    title: "The Ultimate Framer Template Creation Checklist for 2026",
    excerpt: "Follow this comprehensive checklist to build, polish, and publish Framer templates that meet marketplace quality standards and sell consistently.",
    content: "<p>Creating a Framer template that sells requires more than design talent — it demands a systematic approach that covers design quality, technical implementation, documentation, marketplace optimization, and ongoing maintenance. Many talented designers create beautiful templates that fail commercially because they skip critical steps in the production process. This comprehensive checklist distills the best practices of top-selling Framer template creators on Flowbites Marketplace into an actionable guide you can follow for every template you build in 2026. Treat this checklist as your quality assurance process — completing every item before listing ensures your template meets professional standards and buyer expectations from day one.</p><h2>Design and Structure Checklist</h2><p>Begin every template project by defining your target buyer persona and the specific problem your template solves. Research competing templates in your niche on Flowbites and other marketplaces to identify opportunities for differentiation. Design a complete page set — at minimum, include a homepage, about page, contact page, blog listing, blog post, and a 404 error page. Create a design system with consistent spacing scales (multiples of 4 or 8 pixels), a defined type scale with no more than three font families, and a color palette with primary, secondary, neutral, and semantic (success, warning, error) colors stored as Framer design tokens. Build reusable components for every repeated element: buttons, cards, navigation, footer, section headers, and form inputs. Implement component variants for key elements so buyers can customize without rebuilding. Ensure every component uses auto-layout for proper responsive behavior rather than absolute positioning. Test your design at standard breakpoints — 1440px desktop, 1024px tablet, 768px small tablet, and 375px mobile — adjusting layout, font sizes, and spacing at each breakpoint.</p><h2>Technical Quality and Performance Checklist</h2><p>Clean technical implementation separates professional templates from amateur ones. Organize your layer panel with descriptive names — no unnamed frames, no Frame-247 labels. Group related layers into clearly named sections that match your page structure. Ensure all images use responsive sizing and are optimized for web — no 5MB hero images that tank page load times. Implement lazy loading for below-fold images and media. Add hover and focus states to all interactive elements for visual feedback and accessibility. Configure your CMS collections with appropriate field types, sample content, and clear field naming conventions that buyers can understand immediately. Set up page transitions if your template style warrants them, testing that they work smoothly on both desktop and mobile. Validate all internal links, ensuring navigation menus, footer links, and CMS-driven links resolve correctly. Test the published version on real devices — at minimum, the latest iPhone, a mid-range Android phone, and a tablet — catching issues that the editor preview misses. Run a Lighthouse audit targeting scores above 90 for performance, accessibility, and SEO.</p><h2>Documentation, Listing, and Launch Checklist</h2><p>Documentation is the most underestimated factor in template sales and customer satisfaction. Create a comprehensive getting-started guide that walks buyers through remixing the template, connecting their CMS content, updating colors and fonts, replacing images, and publishing to their custom domain. Include a component reference page within the template itself that showcases every component variant and its configuration options. Write a clear changelog that you update with every template revision. For your marketplace listing on Flowbites, create a compelling title that includes your template's primary use case and platform. Write a detailed description covering key features, page count, component count, CMS setup, and any third-party integrations. Capture high-quality preview images showing multiple pages, responsive views, and key design details — your preview images are your primary sales tool. Record a short video walkthrough demonstrating the template's features, customization options, and unique selling points. Set a competitive price based on your template's complexity, page count, and niche value — research comparable templates to find the right price point. After launching, monitor reviews and support requests closely during the first two weeks, addressing issues quickly to maintain positive momentum and protect your marketplace reputation.</p>",
